<section class="start-here">
  <h1>Start here</h1>

  <p class="lead">This is a working cookbook for engineers who run a long-lived
    agent in an orchestrator like OpenClaw or Hermes, while also coding every day
    in tools like Codex CLI, Claude Code, OpenCode, and browser-native model
    sessions. The problem it solves is continuity.</p>

  <figure class="start-here-diagram" set:html={systemOverviewSvg} />

  <p>Your coding harnesses see one repo and one task at a time. Your always-on
    agent should see the whole kitchen: your projects, current work, durable
    decisions, local tools, safety rules, and the handoffs from every coding
    session. Without a shared place for that context, every new session starts
    cold and asks you to re-explain what it should already know.</p>

  <h2>The mental model</h2>

  <p>There is one canonical memory owner and many writers. The owner is the
    always-on agent. It is the single source of truth for durable knowledge:
    what each project is, what changed, which decisions are settled, and which
    rules the stack runs by. In this stack OpenClaw is the tested reference
    memory owner, and Hermes can play the same role.</p>

  <p>The writers are the coding harnesses. Codex CLI, Claude Code, OpenCode, and
    browser-native model sessions do the work, then hand durable context back to
    the owner so future sessions start with the right project state. They write
    handoffs instead of building isolated session memories that no one else can
    see. The owner ingests those handoffs and keeps the shared files current:
    the memory index, the tools and project notes, the agent and safety rules,
    and the memory cards behind them.</p>

  <p>Underneath all of it is a single self-hosted host with a homelab behind it
    for self-hosting, security tooling, and knowledge management. The agent runs
    there, reads and writes the shared memory there, and drives the outputs from
    there: publishing and automation. The pattern generalizes past any one
    machine. One canonical memory owner, many coding harnesses, one shared
    contract for what gets remembered.</p>

  <p>This is not a framework, not a product, and not a tutorial series. It is a
    record of what is actually deployed, why each piece is shaped the way it is,
    and what broke along the way. Lift any single piece, adopt the whole thing,
    or use it as a counterexample. All three are valid.</p>

  <h2>How to read this book</h2>

  <p>New readers should go front to back. The chapters move from the agent stack
    out to knowledge, infrastructure, automation, security, and the rest, so the
    mental model builds in order and each recipe lands with the context it
    assumes.</p>

  <p>Experienced readers can jump straight to any recipe through the contents.
    Each recipe is self-contained. It states what it is and who it is for, why it
    is shaped the way it is, what you need first, the implementation with real
    commands, how to verify it, and the gotchas from real deployments. You do not
    have to read the chapter around a recipe to use it. Pick the one that solves a
    problem you have right now and come back for the rest when you want the why
    behind it.</p>
</section>
